  "prompt": "What is the difference between level and edge triggered flip flops?",
  "response": "The difference between level-triggered and edge-triggered flip-flops lies primarily in the way they respond to input signals and when they change their output state.\n\n### Level-Triggered Flip-Flops\n\n1. **Triggering Mechanism**: Level-triggered flip-flops are sensitive to the level of the input signals. They change their output state as long as the input signal is at a particular stable level (either high or low).\n   \n2. **Types**: Common examples include SR (Set-Reset) latches and D latches that are enabled by a control signal (often called \"enable\"). As long as the enable signal is active (high or low), the output may change according to the inputs.\n\n3. **Behavior**: For these flip-flops, if the enable signal is active and the inputs change, the output will reflect the input directly during that period. This can lead to problems with glitches or unintended state changes if the input signals change frequently while the flip-flop is enabled.\n\n### Edge-Triggered Flip-Flops\n\n1. **Triggering Mechanism**: Edge-triggered flip-flops change their output state only at specific transitions of the clock signal, which are typically the rising edge (from low to high) or the falling edge (from high to low).\n\n2. **Types**: Common examples include D flip-flops, JK flip-flops, and T flip-flops, which are designed to read inputs only during the transition of the clock signal.\n\n3. **Behavior**: In an edge-triggered flip-flop, any change in the input that happens after the triggering edge is ignored until the next triggering edge. This characteristic helps prevent issues such as glitches, as outputs only change in response to defined clock edges.\n\n### Summary\n\n- **Level-triggered flip-flops** respond to the level of input signals while the enable signal is active, allowing for continuous changes in output while enabled.\n- **Edge-triggered flip-flops** respond only on specific transitions (edges) of the clock signal, resulting in more precise control and stability against glitches during operation.\n\nIn summary, the edge-triggered flip-flops offer more predictable timing characteristics and are widely used in synchronous circuits, while level-triggered flip-flops might be employed in situations where continuous observation of input states is required but can be more susceptible to erroneous state changes.",
